          "body": "The crisis begins with a single sentence: 'The LORD forbid me that I should give you the inheritance of my fathers' (21:3). Ahab has framed his request as a reasonable commercial transaction — fair value, or an even trade (21:2). Naboth refuses not out of sentimentality but out of covenant fidelity. Leviticus 25:23 states that the land belongs to Yahweh and may not be sold in perpetuity; Numbers 36:7-9 forbids the transfer of tribal land to another tribe. The ancestral allotment (*nachalah*) was Yahweh's gift to each family, held in trust across generations. Naboth's 'no' is not stubbornness — it is Torah obedience. This is what Ahab misses entirely, and what makes his sullenness so revealing: a king in covenant Israel who does not understand why his subject cannot sell him a vineyard has already broken faith with the covenant he exists to uphold. The whole chapter flows from this foundational misunderstanding of power's proper limits."
